One of the advantages of OSCs is the tunability of the absorption spectrum. Either broadband OPDs, covering the range from UV to NIR, or narrowband devices can be made by choosing appropriate OSCs and device structures. As shown in Fig. 1, the full width at half maximum (FWHM) of the primary detection peak is used to evaluate the selectivity of PDs. A narrower FWHM denotes better selectivity. To quantitatively evaluate the spectra selectivity, the spectral rejection ratio (SRR) is introduced as:Fig. 1
Illustration of required performance metrics of OPDs for different applications6SRR=Rpeak/Rout,\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\mathrm{SRR}={R}_{\mathrm{peak}}/ {R}_{\mathrm{out}},$$\end{document}
where Rpeak is the peak responsivity in the target spectral window and Rout is the responsivity outside the window. Small FWHM and large SRR at different wavelengths are critical for PDs to be used for spectrometer applications. NIR responsivity is required for blood oxygen measurements, bioimaging, spectrometers, and NIR light communications.
